<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-11-29T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-11-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="47" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d47">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/705.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-11-29T13:00:00+08:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 29, 1911—1 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The information requested in your November 28, 3 p.m., came from the
                            Viceroy at Mukden, and the Foreign Office regards it as reliable. The
                            representations were made to me at the same time as to the British,
                            German and Japanese Ministers. The latter denied all knowledge of the
                            matter and promised to telegraph his Government to use its good offices
                            to remove the causes of complaint.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Calhoun.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>